HyperCore – A Next-Generation Hybrid CPU-GPU Lossless Text Compression System
Overview

HyperCore is a proposed next-generation lossless text compression architecture designed specifically for modern heterogeneous computing systems. Unlike traditional compressors that primarily rely on sequential CPU-based processing, HyperCore distributes the workload between multicore CPUs and GPUs, enabling large portions of the compression pipeline to execute in parallel while preserving deterministic, lossless reconstruction.

The project is not intended to be another implementation of CMIX, PAQ, or Zstd. Instead, it aims to rethink the entire compression pipeline from first principles, making it inherently parallel and optimized for today's hardware.

Motivation

Current state-of-the-art text compressors such as CMIX achieve exceptional compression ratios through sophisticated context mixing and adaptive probability prediction. However, they suffer from several limitations:

Extremely slow compression speeds.
Minimal utilization of multicore CPUs.
No practical GPU acceleration.
Sequential prediction models that limit scalability.
General-purpose processing instead of text-aware optimization.

HyperCore addresses these issues by separating highly parallel tasks from inherently sequential tasks and assigning each to the hardware best suited for it.

Core Philosophy

The central philosophy behind HyperCore is:

Compress semantics first, encode bits second.

Rather than immediately applying entropy coding to raw bytes, HyperCore first analyzes the structure of the text, discovers repeated patterns, constructs adaptive dictionaries and grammar representations, builds specialized context models, and only then performs entropy coding.

This reduces redundancy before statistical encoding begins.

Hybrid CPU–GPU Architecture

HyperCore adopts a cooperative processing model.

GPU Responsibilities

The GPU accelerates computationally intensive, massively parallel tasks such as:

Tokenization
UTF-8 validation
Character classification
N-gram extraction
Phrase mining
Rolling hash computation
Frequency analysis
Dictionary candidate generation
Pattern discovery
Grammar candidate generation
Entropy estimation
Parallel rANS encoding

