CPU Responsibilities

The CPU manages operations requiring synchronization and adaptive decision making:

File analysis
Compression scheduling
Dictionary optimization
Grammar optimization
Context selection
Probability mixing
Archive generation
Metadata management
Integrity verification
Context Islands (Novel Concept)

One of the key innovations is Context Islands.

Traditional compressors often build a single global statistical model for the entire input. HyperCore instead partitions the document into semantic regions such as:

Natural language
Source code
JSON
XML
CSV
Markdown
Log files

Each region is compressed using a specialized context model.

This improves prediction quality because each model learns statistics only from similar content instead of mixing unrelated structures.

Multi-Level Dictionary System

Instead of using a single dictionary, HyperCore employs a hierarchical approach:

Global dictionary
Document-specific dictionary
Block-specific dictionary

Each level captures redundancy at different scales.

The encoder dynamically selects the most efficient representation.

Grammar-Based Structure Compression

Beyond repeated words, HyperCore identifies recurring structural patterns and converts them into reusable grammar rules.

Examples include:

Common programming constructs
JSON objects
XML elements
Markdown patterns
Log templates

These structures are represented once and referenced throughout the archive.

Adaptive Prediction

Rather than evaluating every prediction model for every symbol, HyperCore dynamically selects only the most relevant models based on the current context.

Possible predictors include:

Character model
Word model
Phrase model
Dictionary model
Grammar model
Structural model
Optional lightweight neural predictor

Their outputs are combined using an adaptive probability mixer.

GPU-Friendly Entropy Coding

Instead of relying solely on arithmetic coding, HyperCore uses parallel-friendly rANS (Range Asymmetric Numeral Systems), which offers high compression efficiency while allowing significantly greater parallelism.

The GPU performs entropy coding across multiple blocks simultaneously.

Parallel Pipeline

The compression pipeline is designed so that CPU and GPU remain active concurrently.

While the GPU processes one block:

The CPU prepares the next block.
Previous blocks are archived.
Metadata is generated.
Dictionaries are updated.

This minimizes idle hardware and maximizes throughput.

Expected Advantages

If successfully implemented, HyperCore aims to provide:

Compression ratios approaching CMIX on text-heavy datasets.
Significantly faster compression through CPU-GPU cooperation.
Efficient scaling across many CPU cores and modern GPUs.
Optimized performance for source code, documentation, logs, JSON, XML, Markdown, and similar text formats.
A modular architecture that supports future predictors, plugins, and research extensions.
Research Contribution

The primary research contribution is architectural, not merely algorithmic.

Instead of inventing a single new entropy coder or prediction model, HyperCore proposes a complete redesign of the lossless text compression pipeline around heterogeneous computing.

The novelty lies in:

Semantic-aware preprocessing.
Context Islands.
Hierarchical adaptive dictionaries.
GPU-first pattern discovery.
Hybrid CPU-GPU scheduling.
Parallel-friendly entropy coding.
Modular predictor architecture.

Together, these ideas seek to narrow the long-standing gap between maximum compression ratio and practical compression speed, making CMIX-class compression more feasible for real-world use on modern hardware.

